In this article, the author discusses the progress made in combating the HIV epidemic and the efforts being made to address gaps in diagnosing, caring for, and preventing HIV. The author highlights the announcement made during the State of the Union Address to end the HIV epidemic in the US within 10 years. They also mention the launch of the "Ending the HIV Epidemic: A Plan for America" through the Department of Health and Human Services, which requested $291 million in funding to improve diagnosis, treatment, care, and protection for individuals living with HIV. The article also mentions a large private donation of pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) medication to help reduce the risk of HIV infection for uninsured individuals. The author emphasizes the importance of testing and treatment in reducing new HIV infections and sets a goal to reduce new infections by 75% in the next 5 years and at least 90% in the next decade. The article concludes by encouraging Americans to learn more about protecting their health and seeking out the necessary care.